          'Arc flash is a sudden, violent release of energy caused by an electrical fault — phase-to-phase, phase-to-ground, or phase-to-neutral. The resulting arc plasma reaches approximately 35,000°F, nearly four times the surface temperature of the sun. NFPA 70E quantifies the thermal hazard as incident energy, expressed in calories per square centimeter (cal/cm²). At 1.2 cal/cm², bare skin sustains a second-degree burn. Arc flash injuries can occur without any contact with the conductors — radiant and convective heat energy travel outward from the arc point, which is why working distance and PPE are so critical.',
