              correctScenario: 'eewp-required',
              correctFeedback: 'Correct. Energized work is legitimately justified — de-energizing would cause a major uncontrolled outage to production systems. But justified energized work still requires an EEWP. The permit documents why de-energization is infeasible, identifies the PPE required, and gets proper authorization before you approach the bus. Measurements are energized work under NFPA 70E.',
              incorrectFeedback: 'Voltage measurements on an energized bus are energized electrical work under NFPA 70E — there is no measurement exemption. The work may be justified given the critical load, but "justified" does not mean "uncontrolled." An EEWP is required to document the justification and specify controls before proceeding.',
